.Dd June 15, 2026
.Dt CRASHEDIT 1
.Os
.Sh NAME
.Nm crashedit
.Nd FTN (FidoNet) message reader and editor with JAM messagebase support
.Sh SYNOPSIS
.Nm crashedit
.Op Ar configfile
.Sh DESCRIPTION
.Nm crashedit
is a full-featured FTN message reader and editor designed for FidoNet systems.
It reads and writes JAM messagebases, supports multiple character encodings,
ANSI art rendering, file requests, attachments, nodelist integration, and
Unicode glyph selection.
.Sh GETTING STARTED
When you run
.Nm crashedit
without arguments, it looks for a configuration file named
.Pa crashedit.conf
in the current directory.
If you specify a path as an argument, it uses that configuration file instead.
.Ss First Run - Initial Configuration
If no configuration file exists,
.Nm crashedit
automatically opens the Setup screen where you must configure essential settings.
The Setup screen is organized into tabs that you navigate with the arrow keys and Enter.
.Pp
The
.Em Identity
tab requires:
.Bl -bullet
.It
Your SysOp name (full name)
.It
At least one AKA address in FidoNet format (z:n/f.p, for example 2:341/207)
.It
The area file path (typically areas.golded generated by crashexport)
.El
.Pp
The
.Em Paths
tab configures file locations including the area file, FREQ outbound directory,
and optional tagline/template files.
.Pp
The
.Em Display
tab controls how messages are shown - whether to display hidden lines,
kludges, ANSI colors, and message list formatting options.
.Pp
The
.Em Editor
tab sets editor preferences like tearline, INTL handling, auto-wrap column,
quote margin, undo levels, and line number display.
.Pp
The
.Em Messages
tab configures automatic greeting, attribution lines, and signature insertion.
.Pp
The
.Em Colour/Font
tab sets color schemes and font options (platform-specific).
.Pp
Press F10 to save your configuration and continue to the main interface.
.Sh AREA LIST - MAIN INTERFACE
The main screen displays all available message areas in a table format.
Each row shows the area number, short name (tag), description, total message count,
and unread message count.
.Ss Navigating Areas
Use the arrow keys or j/k to move through the area list.
Page Up/Down moves one screen at a time, while Home/End jumps to the first or last area.
Press Enter on an area to open it and view its messages.
.Ss Finding Areas
Press
.Sy /
to activate fuzzy search - type part of an area name and the list filters
in real-time to show matching areas.
Press
.Sy G
or g to activate type-ahead picker - type to filter areas in real-time while
navigating with arrows, then press Enter to open the selected area.
Press ESC to cancel and return to normal view.
.Ss Sorting Areas
Press
.Sy s
to change the sort order.
You can specify sort criteria like A (AKA), D (description), E (echoid),
T (type), U (unread count), or Y (unread tier).
For example, "U+E" sorts areas with unread messages first, then by name.
.Ss Managing Areas
Press
.Sy C
or Alt+C to perform catch-up - marking messages as read.
You can choose to mark only the current area or all areas at once.
Press
.Sy R
or Alt+S to rescan all areas and refresh message counts.
Press
.Sy Ctrl+F
to create a file request (FREQ) to request files from remote nodes.
Press
.Sy P
to perform an advanced search across all areas.
Press
.Sy S
to return to the Setup configuration screen.
Press
.Sy q
or ESC to quit the program.
.Sh MESSAGE LIST - VIEWING MESSAGES IN AN AREA
When you open an area, you see the Message List showing all messages with their
date, sender, recipient, and subject.
Unread messages are highlighted in a different color.
.Ss Navigating Messages
Use arrow keys or j/k to select messages.
Page Up/Down moves through the list one screen at a time.
Home/End jumps to the first or last message.
Press Space or Enter to read the selected message.
.Ss Creating and Managing Messages
Press
.Sy n
or N to write a new message.
Press
.Sy r
or R to reply to the selected message.
Press
.Sy e
or E to edit a message you wrote (you can only edit your own messages).
Press
.Sy d
or D or Delete to delete a message (with confirmation).
Press
.Sy g
or G to jump to a specific message number by entering the number.
.Ss Searching Messages
Press
.Sy /
for quick search by From, To, or Subject fields.
Type your search pattern and press Enter to find matches.
Press
.Sy P
for advanced search with options to search headers, body, or both across
all areas.
.Ss Returning
Press
.Sy q
or Left arrow or ESC to return to the Area List.
.Sh READER - READING MESSAGE CONTENT
The Reader displays the full content of a message with navigation and display options.
.Ss Reading Messages
Use arrow keys to scroll through the message line by line.
Page Up/Down or b/B moves one screen at a time.
Home/End jumps to the start or end of the message.
Press Right or n to move to the next message in the area.
Press Left or p to move to the previous message.
Press Ctrl+Right or Ctrl+Left to follow the reply thread and navigate through
related messages.
Press Ctrl+G to scroll to the top of the message.
Press Ctrl+K to scroll to the bottom of the message.
Press Alt+G to jump to a specific line number by entering the line number.
.Ss Display Options
Press
.Sy a
or A to toggle ANSI rendering.
When enabled, ANSI color codes are interpreted and displayed with colors.
When disabled, the codes are shown as plain text (useful if colors make reading difficult).
.Pp
Press
.Sy c
or C to change the display character encoding.
Options include CP437 (traditional DOS/FTN), CP850, CP866 (Cyrillic),
LATIN-1/2, CP1252, UTF-8, or AUTO.
AUTO mode detects the encoding from the ^ACHRS or ^ACHARSET kludge in the message.
.Pp
Press
.Sy k
or K to toggle visibility of kludges (control lines like ^A MSGID, SEEN-BY, Via).
Press
.Sy v
or V to toggle display of hidden lines.
.Ss Acting on Messages
Press
.Sy r
or R to reply to the current message.
Press
.Sy e
or E to edit the message (only your own messages).
Press
.Sy N
or Insert to write a new message.
Press F3 or Alt+P to jump to the previous search match.
Press F4 or Alt+N to change your AKA (sending address) for netmail.
Press F7 or w/W to save the message to a text file.
Press d or D or Delete to delete the message.
Press F1 or Alt+Y for help.
Press q or Q or ESC to return to the Message List.
.Sh EDITOR - WRITING MESSAGES
The Editor is a full-featured text editor for composing messages.
It has two modes: header fields (From, To, Subject, DAddr) and message body.
.Ss Header Fields
When you start writing a message, the cursor begins in the From field.
Use Tab, Down arrow, or Ctrl+N to move to the next field (From → To → Subject → DAddr → Body).
Use Up arrow or Ctrl+P to move to the previous field.
Press Enter in any header field to jump directly to the message body.
.Pp
Within a field, use arrow keys to move the cursor, Backspace/Delete to delete characters,
and Home/End to jump to the start or end of the field.
.Ss Writing the Message Body
Once in the body, type your message normally.
Press Enter to create new lines.
Use arrow keys to navigate, Page Up/Down to scroll through long messages.
Use Ctrl+Left/Right to move by words instead of characters.
.Pp
Press Backspace or Delete to delete characters.
Press Ctrl+Y to delete the entire current line.
Press Ctrl+T to delete the word to the right of the cursor.
Press Ctrl+_ to delete the word to the left.
Press Insert or Alt+I to toggle between insert and overwrite mode.
.Ss Saving and Exiting
Press F2 or Ctrl+S to save your message.
The message is saved to the JAM messagebase but not sent immediately -
your mailer will handle the actual transmission.
Press F10, ESC, or Ctrl+Q to cancel editing.
If you have unsaved changes, you'll be asked to confirm: Y discards changes and exits,
N returns you to the editor.
.Ss Character Encoding
Press F3 or Alt+H to open the charset picker.
This lets you set both the display charset (how you see the message) and
the output charset (how the message is saved).
UTF-8 is recommended for output for maximum compatibility with modern systems.
.Ss Changing AKA (Netmail Only)
Press F4 or Ctrl+A to change your AKA (sending address).
In echo areas, the AKA is locked to the area's configuration.
In netmail areas, you can select from your configured AKAs.
This determines which address appears as the sender.
.Ss Block Operations
To work with a block of text:
.Bl -enum
.It
Press F6 to mark the block start (the cursor position is anchored).
.It
Move the cursor to where you want the block to end - the text between the anchor
and cursor is highlighted.
.It
Press Ctrl+C to copy the block to both the internal clipboard and the system
clipboard (if available on your platform).
.It
Press Ctrl+X to cut the block (copy and remove from the message).
.It
Move to where you want to paste and press Ctrl+V to paste from the clipboard.
.It
Press Ctrl+O to export the selected block to a file on disk.
.El
.Ss Undo and Redo
Press Ctrl+Z to undo your last change.
Press Alt+Z to redo an undone change.
The undo stack depth is configurable in Setup (default 50 levels).
.Ss Search and Replace
Press F5 or Alt+S to enter a search pattern.
Press Ctrl+R for interactive find and replace - you'll be prompted for both
search and replacement text, and can choose to replace each occurrence individually
or all at once.
.Pp
Press F3 or Alt+P to jump to the previous search match.
Press F4 or Alt+N to jump to the next search match.
Press F6 or Alt+B to replace all occurrences (in search mode).
.Ss Navigation
Press Ctrl+G to jump to the start of the document.
Press Ctrl+K to jump to the end of the document.
Press Alt+G to jump to a specific line number (enter the line number when prompted).
.Ss Text Formatting
Press Ctrl+W to reformat the current paragraph to the configured column width
(default 75 characters).
This is useful for cleaning up quoted text or ensuring lines don't exceed FTN limits.
.Pp
Press Alt+Q to toggle between hard-wrap and soft-wrap modes.
Hard-wrap inserts carriage returns at the column boundary (traditional FTN style).
Soft-wrap only wraps visually without inserting line breaks (modern editor style).
.Ss Kludges and Attributes
Press F8 or Alt+K to view and edit kludges - the FTN control lines like
^A MSGID, ^A REPLY, ^A INTL, etc. that are normally hidden.
.Pp
Press F9 or Alt+R to toggle message attributes like Private, Crash, Hold, Sent,
and other flags that control how the message is handled by the tosser.
.Ss Nodelist Integration
If you have loaded nodelists using the INCLUDE directive in your configuration,
you can use the nodelist picker.
Press F10 or Alt+P while in a header field to open the nodelist picker -
type to filter by name, select a node, and it fills in the To and DAddr fields.
Press F11 or Alt+V to open the nodelist browser in read-only mode for reference.
.Ss Unicode Glyph Picker
Press Alt+U to open the Unicode glyph picker.
This displays a grid of Unicode characters organized by blocks (Latin, Greek,
Cyrillic, Hebrew, Arabic, CJK, Emojis, etc.).
You can filter by block, navigate the grid, or enter a hexadecimal codepoint directly.
Select a character to insert it at the cursor position - useful for inserting
special characters not available on your keyboard.
.Sh NETMAIL FEATURES
Netmail (private mail) areas have additional features not available in echo areas.
.Ss File Attachments
You can attach files to netmail messages to send them to other nodes.
.Pp
Press Alt+A to add an attachment - you'll be prompted to select a file from disk.
You can attach up to 32 files per message.
The file names appear in the subject line (limited to 71 characters by FTS-1).
.Pp
Press Alt+X to remove the selected attachment.
Press Alt+M to list all current attachments.
Press Alt+C to clear all attachments.
.Pp
When the message is sent, your mailer will encode the attachments and the
recipient's mailer will decode them and place them in their inbound directory.
.Ss Carbon Copy (CC)
To send copies of a message to multiple recipients, add CC lines in the message body:
.Dl CC: John Doe 2:341/207@fidonet
.Dl CC: Jane Smith 2:341/201@fidonet
.Pp
The format can be just an address (uses the To field name) or with a specific name.
CrashEdit converts these to ^ACC kludges and the message is sent to all specified recipients.
.Ss AKA Selection
Press Ctrl+A or F4 to change which of your configured AKAs appears as the sender.
This is useful when you have multiple FidoNet addresses and want to choose
the appropriate one for a particular message.
.Sh FILE REQUEST (FREQ)
File Request lets you request files from remote FidoNet nodes without manually
downloading them.
.Pp
Press Ctrl+F from the Area List or Message List to open the File Request screen.
.Bl -enum
.It
Enter the FTN address of the node that has the files you want.
.It
Select the outbound mode:
.Bl -tag -width "XXX" -compact
.It ASO
Amiga Style Outbound - flat files in a single directory with names like zone.net.node.point.flo
.It BSO
BinkleyStyle - files organized by zones in subdirectories
.It BSO+ext
BSO with hexadecimal zone extension
.El
.It
Add files to your request by pressing A and entering file names.
.It
Optionally press P to set a password if the node requires one.
.It
Press W (write) to generate the .req file.
.El
.Pp
The generated .req file is placed in your outbound directory (configured in Setup).
Your mailer will process this file and send the request to the destination node,
which will respond by sending the requested files to your inbound directory.
.Pp
This requires the OUTBOUND directory to be configured in crashedit.conf
pointing to your mailer's outbound directory.
.Sh ADVANCED SEARCH
Press P from the Message List or Area List to perform an advanced search.
.Pp
A popup appears with search options:
.Bl -tag -width "XXX" -compact
.It Pattern
The text to search for (required)
.It Headers
Search in From, To, and Subject fields
.It Body
Search in the message body text
.It All Areas
Search across all areas instead of just the current area
.It Max Hits
Limit the number of results (0 = unlimited)
.It Case Sensitive
Match uppercase and lowercase exactly
.It Whole Word
Match only complete words
.El
.Pp
Press Enter to execute the search.
The results show a list of areas that contain matching messages.
Select an area to view the matching messages within that area.
.Pp
For quick searches by From/To/Subject only, use / in the Message List instead.
.Sh NODELIST SUPPORT
CrashEdit can load FTS-5000 format nodelists and pointlists into memory for
quick node lookup.
.Pp
To enable this, add INCLUDE directives to your configuration file pointing
to your nodelist files:
.Dl INCLUDE /path/to/nodelist
.Pp
Once loaded, you can use the nodelist picker to select recipients without
remembering addresses.
Press F10 or Alt+P in a header field to open the picker - type to filter by name,
use arrows to navigate, and press Enter to select.
.Pp
Press F11 or Alt+V to open the nodelist browser in read-only mode for reference.
.Sh CHARACTER ENCODING
FTN messages traditionally use various character encodings depending on the
platform and region.
CrashEdit supports multiple encodings for compatibility:
.Pp
.Bl -bullet
.It
CP437 - Default for reading, traditional DOS/FTN encoding
.It
CP850 - Multilingual DOS encoding
.It
CP865 - Nordic encoding
.It
CP866 - Cyrillic encoding
.It
LATIN-1/2 - ISO-8859 Western/Central European
.It
CP1252 - Windows encoding
.It
UTF-8 - Default for writing, full Unicode support
.It
AUTO - Display mode only, detects encoding from ^ACHRS/^ACHARSET kludge
.El
.Pp
CrashEdit maintains two independent charset settings:
.Bl -bullet
.It
View charset - How messages are displayed on screen
.It
Save charset - How messages you write are encoded when saved
.El
.Pp
Use F3 or Alt+H in the editor to change both simultaneously.
For maximum modern compatibility, use UTF-8 for the save charset.
.Sh ANSI ART
Many FTN messages contain ANSI art - text with color codes for visual effects.
.Pp
Press a or A in the Reader to toggle ANSI rendering.
When enabled, escape sequences are interpreted and displayed with colors.
When disabled, the codes are shown as plain text (e.g., [0;32m) which is useful
if the colors make reading difficult or if you want to see the raw formatting.
.Sh LINE NUMBERS
CrashEdit can display line numbers in the Editor for reference.
.Pp
Press Alt+D in the editor to toggle line number display.
This is helpful when editing or reviewing specific parts of long messages.
.Sh SOFT/HARD WRAP MODE
CrashEdit supports two wrapping modes:
.Pp
.Bl -tag -width "XXX" -compact
.It Soft-wrap
Lines wrap visually at the screen edge without inserting line breaks.
This is the default for modern text editors.
.It Hard-wrap
Carriage returns are inserted at the configured column boundary.
This is traditional FTN style and may be required for compatibility with
some systems.
.El
.Pp
Press Alt+Q to toggle between modes.
The default column width is configurable in Setup (default 75 characters).
.Sh CLIPBOARD INTEGRATION
CrashEdit integrates with the system clipboard on supported platforms:
.Pp
.Bl -bullet
.It
Unix (X11): Requires xclip to be installed
.It
Unix (Wayland): Requires wl-clipboard to be installed
.It
Windows: Uses Windows clipboard automatically
.It
Amiga: Uses clipboard.device
.It
SSH/headless: Falls back to internal block only (no external clipboard)
.El
.Pp
When you copy or cut a block, it's copied to both the internal clipboard
and the system clipboard if available.
When you paste, CrashEdit tries the system clipboard first, then falls back
to the internal block if the external clipboard is unavailable or empty.
.Sh EXITING THE PROGRAM
From the Area List, press q or ESC to quit.
If there are no pending operations, the program exits immediately.
.Pp
From other screens, press q or ESC repeatedly to return to the Area List,
then press q to quit.
.Pp
From the Editor, press F10, ESC, or Ctrl+Q to cancel editing.
If you have unsaved changes, you'll be prompted to confirm:
Y discards changes and exits, N returns you to the editor.
.Pp
Configuration changes are saved automatically when you exit the Setup screen.
Message changes are saved only when you explicitly press F2 or Ctrl+S.
.Sh FILES
.Bl -tag -width "~/.crashedit.conf" -compact
.It Pa crashedit.conf
Configuration file (in current directory or specified path)
.It Pa crashedit.conf.example
Example configuration file with all available options documented
.It Pa areas.golded
Area list file generated by crashexport (required for operation)
.El
.Sh EXIT STATUS
.Ex -std
.Sh EXAMPLES
Start with default configuration in current directory:
.Dl $ crashedit
.Pp
Start with a specific configuration file:
.Dl $ crashedit /home/user/.crashedit.conf
.Sh SEE ALSO
.Xr crashmail 1 ,
.Xr crashexport 1 ,
.Xr crashgetnode 1
.Sh AUTHORS
.An Tanausú M. Aq ervras@aim.com
.Sh CAVEATS
.Nm crashedit
requires JAM messagebases and an area file generated by crashexport.
File requests require the OUTBOUND directory to be configured and a compatible
mailer.
Clipboard integration on Unix requires xclip (X11) or wl-clipboard (Wayland).
.Sh BUGS
Report bugs to the author or via GitHub issues.
